{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When multiple product teams build on the same GenAI platform, they independently discover the same problems, run the same experiments, and make the same mistakes. Without a cross-team coordination structure, this is pure waste: three teams each spend two weeks discovering that a particular chunking strategy degrades RAG recall, when one team's finding could have prevented the other two from repeating the investigation. Cross-team improvement forums and guilds are the mechanism for converting individual team learning into shared organizational knowledge."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "GenAI cross-team improvement structure: platform team at center connected to four product teams, coordinated by three forums (Prompt Engineering Guild biweekly, Eval and Safety Forum monthly, Architecture Council quarterly) plus an async learnings channel"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Problem Guilds Solve"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Without cross-team coordination, each product team operates as an independent learning silo:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Prompt engineering breakthroughs discovered by Team A are not shared with Team B — both teams spend time on similar prompt optimization cycles."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Eval benchmarks are duplicated across teams with slight variations — no shared baseline for comparing quality across products."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Safety red-team sets are maintained independently — the bypass pattern found by Team C's security review never reaches Team D's eval set."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Architectural decisions made by one team (e.g. switching to a new RAG framework) are not visible to other teams until they run into the same limitations."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Guilds are not committees that produce documents. They are the mechanism by which one team's hard-won operational knowledge becomes another team's week-one standard practice."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The three forum types below address different timescales of learning: immediate tactical improvements (prompt engineering guild), monthly quality and safety calibration (eval and safety forum), and quarterly architectural direction (architecture council)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Forum 1: Prompt Engineering Guild (Biweekly)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Purpose and Scope"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The prompt engineering guild is a biweekly 60-minute session where one guild representative from each product team shares the most significant prompt engineering finding from the past two weeks. The output is a shared prompt pattern library that all teams draw from."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Guild Structure"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Rotating demo (20 min).",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " One team presents a prompt engineering finding: a pattern that improved eval score, a failure mode discovered, or a technique that reduced token cost. Demos are required to include before/after eval numbers — no anecdotes without data."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Pattern library updates (15 min).",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " The team votes on whether the presented finding should be added to the shared prompt pattern library. Additions require: an eval result, a code snippet, and a documented context (which use cases this applies to)."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Open floor (20 min).",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " Any representative can raise a prompt engineering question, describe a problem they are stuck on, or request feedback on a current experiment design."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Action items (5 min).",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " Any work items created (pattern library PRs, follow-up experiments) get owners before the session ends."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Shared Prompt Pattern Library"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The pattern library is a versioned repository, not a wiki page. Each entry is a structured document:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "markdown"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Pattern: Chain-of-Thought for Multi-Step Reasoning\n\n## Summary\nInserting \"Let's think step by step:\" before the answer request improves\naccuracy on multi-step reasoning tasks by 8–15% on our internal eval set.\n\n## When to use\n- Tasks requiring more than 2 logical steps\n- Math or code explanation tasks\n- Tasks where the model frequently skips intermediate reasoning\n\n## When NOT to use\n- Simple classification tasks (adds tokens without quality gain)\n- Latency-sensitive paths where token count is constrained\n- Tasks where the model's intermediate reasoning is unreliable (hallucination risk)\n\n## Example\n\n### Before\n```\n{user_question}\nAnswer:\n```\n\n### After\n```\n{user_question}\nLet's think through this step by step:\n```\n\n## Eval results\n- Task: support ticket classification (Team A eval set, n=500)\n- Before: 0.782 exact-match\n- After:  0.841 exact-match (+7.5%)\n- Latency impact: +0.3s mean (18% increase — acceptable for non-RT path)\n- Token cost impact: +12% input tokens\n\n## Context\nDiscovered by Team A, 2025-06-18.\nValidated by Team C on code explanation task: +9.2% accuracy, similar latency profile.\nAdded to library: 2025-07-01.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Forum 2: Eval and Safety Forum (Monthly)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Purpose and Scope"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The eval and safety forum is a monthly 90-minute session focused on maintaining shared quality standards and a common safety baseline across all product teams. It is the forum that prevents teams from drifting into incompatible quality definitions."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Forum Agenda"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "markdown"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "## Eval & Safety Forum — Monthly Agenda\n\n### 1. Shared eval benchmark review (20 min)\n- Review the cross-team quality dashboard: each team's eval score trend for the past 30 days\n- Flag any team with a significant downward trend (> 2%) for a follow-up\n- Identify cases where team A's benchmark improvement could benefit team B\n\n### 2. Red-team set synchronization (25 min)\n- Each team shares any new adversarial examples found in the past month\n- Vote on additions to the shared red-team set\n- Review refusal rate trends across teams — a divergence signals different model\n  behavior or guardrail configurations\n\n### 3. Cross-team incident review (20 min)\n- Any safety incident from any team is presented in summary form (blameless)\n- Identify whether the root cause could affect other teams\n- If yes: mandate that all teams add the same red-team example\n\n### 4. Benchmark calibration (15 min)\n- Are teams using the same rubric definitions for LLM-as-judge scoring?\n- If rubric drift is detected (scores diverging without product differentiation),\n  recalibrate to a shared anchoring set\n- Agree on any rubric updates and propagate to all teams\n\n### 5. Action items (10 min)\n- Red-team additions with owners\n- Cross-team experiments\n- Benchmark calibration updates\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Cross-Team Quality Dashboard"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from dataclasses import dataclass\nfrom datetime import date\n\n@dataclass\nclass TeamQualitySnapshot:\n    team_name: str\n    product: str\n    eval_score_current: float\n    eval_score_30d_ago: float\n    fitness_warn_count_30d: int\n    fitness_block_count_30d: int\n    refusal_rate_current: float\n    pii_incidents_30d: int\n\n    @property\n    def score_delta(self) -> float:\n        return self.eval_score_current - self.eval_score_30d_ago\n\n    @property\n    def needs_review(self) -> bool:\n        return (\n            self.score_delta < -0.02\n            or self.fitness_block_count_30d > 0\n            or self.pii_incidents_30d > 0\n            or self.refusal_rate_current < 0.97\n        )\n\ndef render_cross_team_dashboard(snapshots: list[TeamQualitySnapshot]) -> str:\n    lines = [\"Cross-Team Quality Dashboard\", \"=\" * 50]\n    for s in snapshots:\n        flag = \" ⚠\" if s.needs_review else \"\"\n        lines.append(\n            f\"{s.team_name} ({s.product}){flag}\\n\"\n            f\"  Eval: {s.eval_score_current:.3f} ({s.score_delta:+.3f} vs 30d ago)\\n\"\n            f\"  Safety: refusal={s.refusal_rate_current:.1%}, PII incidents={s.pii_incidents_30d}\\n\"\n            f\"  Fitness: {s.fitness_warn_count_30d} warns, {s.fitness_block_count_30d} blocks\"\n        )\n    return \"\\n\".join(lines)\n"
          }
        ]
      },
